protected_spaces_details.description: Provision for children and young people

description: Retention of the main building and conversion to 106 residential units, demolition of all remaining buildings and construction of 936 houses and flats (between 2 and 10 storeys in height), together with the creation of a new access at Lodge Avenue, associated landscaping and car parking (full details) and the erection of a primary school (outline proposal with details reserved for subsequent approval)
decision_conditions: The school site development permitted shall be begun  before the expiration of two years from the date of approval of the last of the reserved matters to be approved. Reason:To comply with Section 92 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 (as amended by S.51 of the Planning and Compulsory Purchase Act  2004)

No development approved by this permission shall be commenced prior to a contaminated land assessment and associated remedial strategy, together with a timetable of works, being submitted to the Local Planning Authority for approval:a) The contaminated land assessment shall include a desk study to be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for approval. The desk study shall detail the history of the site uses and propose a site investigation strategy based on the relevant information discovered by the desk study. The strategy shall be approved by the Local Planning Authority prior to investigations commencing on site.b) The site investigation, including relevant soil, soil gas, surface and groundwater sampling, shall be carried out by a suitably qualified and accredited consultant/contractor in accordance with a Quality Assured sampling and analysis methodology.c) A site investigation report detailing all investigative works and sampling on site, together with the results of analysis, risk assessment to any receptors and a proposed remediation strategy shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority. The Local Planning Authority shall approve such remedial works as required prior to any remediation commencing on site. The works shall be of such a nature as to render harmless the identified contamination given the proposed end-use of the site and surrounding environment including any controlled waters.d) Approved remediation works shall be carried out in full on site under a quality assurance scheme to demonstrate compliance with the proposed methodology and best practice guidance. If during the works contamination is encountered which has not previously been identified then the additional contamination shall be fully assessed and an appropriate remediation scheme agreed with the Local Planning Authority. e) Upon completion of the works, this condition shall not be discharged until a closure report has been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority. The closure report shall include details of the proposed remediation works and quality assurance certificates to show that the works have been carried out in full in accordance with the approved methodology. Details of any post-remedial sampling and analysis to show the site has reached the required clean-up criteria shall be included in the closure report together with the necessary documentation detailing what waste materials have been removed from the site. ReasonTo prevent pollution of the water environment and in order to quantify any hazards already existing on the site in accordance with Policy G28 of the Unitary Development Plan.

No phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall commence until a drainage strategy for that phase detailing any on and/or off site drainage works, has been submitted to and approved by, the local planning authority in consultation with the sewerage undertaker.  No discharge of foul or surface water from the site shall be accepted into the public system until the drainage works referred to in the approved strategy have been completed.Reason:In order to prevent the pollution of the water environment and to minimise surface water run off in accordance with policy G38 of the UDP.

No infiltration of surface water drainage into the ground is permitted other than with the express written consent of the Local Planning Authority, which may be given for those parts of the site where it has been demonstrated that there is no resultant unacceptable risk to controlled waters. Reason:In order to prevent the pollution of the water environment in accordance with policy G38 of the UDP.

Prior to the commencement of any phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) the applicant shall submit a scheme detailing measures to minimise the water consumption of that completed phase of the development.  The scheme shall be implemented in accordance with the approved details and thereafter maintained. Reason:In order to conserve water and to reduce the demand on the mains drainage system and in accordance with policy 4A.14 of the London Plan.

No phase of the development hereby permitted (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall commence until a Method Statement detailing mitigation measures to minimise exposure to air pollution related to that phase has been submitted to and approved by to the Local Planning Authority.  The Method Statement shall be implemented in accordance with the approved details.Reason:In the interests of the health and well being of the future occupants of the site and neighbouring residents and in accordance with policy G39 of the UDP.

No phase of the development hereby permitted (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall be commenced until a planting scheme for that phase, comprising trees and shrubs, to maximise vegetation absorption and filtration of air to improve air quality in areas adjacent to local traffic has been submitted to and approved by to the Local Planning Authority.  The planting scheme shall be implemented in accordance with the approved details.Reason:In the interests of the health and well being of the future occupants of the site and neighbouring residents and in accordance with policy G39 of the UDP.

Details of the proposed green roofs and green walls including their type, location and specific purpose together with a maintenance schedule shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority prior to the construction of any building containing the green roof. The primary purpose of the green roofs will be to promote biodiversity.  The green roofs shall be constructed in accordance with the approved details and thereafter maintained in accordance with the approved maintenance schedule.Reason:In the interests of reducing the impact of the development on the mains drainage system, enhancing the insulation of the building, and contributing to bio-diversity and improved air quality, and in accordance with policies DE9, H20 and G46 of the UDP.

No phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall commence until the applicant has provided to the Local Planning Authority the Code for Sustainable Homes site registration number which will set out the level that the development is aiming to achieve for that phase and the codes requirements for the developer as issued by the BRE.  Each phase should be registered with the BRE, a maximum of six months before commencement of that phase.   The scheme will seek to achieve a minimum of code level 3, but must also demonstrate best endeavours to ensure that code level 4 is achieved where possible.  Once the notional SAP ratings for the development are known a design stage certificate must be submitted to the Local Planning Authority verifying the code level that will be achieved.  The scheme should achieve a minimum of code level 3. A post construction certificate stating that the residential units for each phase have achieved a minimum of code level 3 shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to the first occupation of any residential unit within that phase unless otherwise agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority. Reason:In order to reduce the environmental impact of the development and in accordance with policy 4A.2 of the London Plan.

The residential development hereby approved shall seek to reduce total CO2 emissions from a Building Regulations compliant scenario as of November 2008 by 41.5% in accordance with the submitted energy strategy which shall be implemented.  The technologies employed on site to deliver the 41.5% Carbon Dioxide Reduction (as set out in the Energy Strategy) will be monitored for 12 months commencing within 3 months from the completion of the development and details of the annual energy generation shall be provided to the local planning authority within 28 days from the end of the monitoring period.  Should less than the 41.5% Carbon Dioxide Reduction target be achieved then a supplementary energy strategy designed to make up the renewable energy shortfall shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority.  The approved supplementary energy strategy (if required) shall be implemented within 6 months of the end of the monitoring period.Reason:In order to reduce the carbon emissions of the development in accordance with policy 4A.1 of the London Plan.

Details of a strategy to mitigate the loss of mature trees on the site shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of the development.  The strategy shall minimise the impact on bio-diversity and shall include a bat inspection and shall ensure felling or lopping is programmed outside the bird nesting season. The strategy shall be implemented in accordance with the approved details.  Reason:In order to mitigate the loss of trees resulting from the development in the interests of visual amenity and bio-diversity and in accordance with policies DE17 and G46 of the UDP.

A parking strategy setting out the allocation of parking spaces shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of the development.  The parking strategy shall be implemented and thereafter maintained in accordance with the approved details.Reason:In order to ensure adequate parking facilities for each part of the residential development in the interest of the residential amenity of the future occupants and in accordance with Strategic Policy X of the UDP.

The accessible parking bays shown on the approved drawings shall be clearly marked with a British Standard disabled symbol and permanently retained for the use of disabled persons and their vehicles and for no other purpose.Reason:To ensure and promote easier access for disabled persons to the approved building in accordance with Policy C15 of the Unitary Development Plan.

No phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall commence until details of the cycle parking facilities have been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.  The submission should include details of the security, monitoring, and access arrangements for the cycle parking facilities.  No residential unit within any phase shall be occupied until the approved details for that phase have been implemented. Thereafter, the approved cycle parking facilities shall be permanently retained.Reason:In the interests of promoting cycling as a safe, efficient and non-polluting mode of transport and the residential amenity of future residents and in accordance with Strategic Policy X of the UDP.

No buildings within the residential development hereby permitted shall be occupied until there has been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority a Green Travel Plan for the site which shall include proposals for minimising car-borne travel and encouraging walking, cycling and the use of public transport.  The approved Green Travel Plan shall be implemented and monitored in accordance with the approved scheme.Reason:In view of the limited on site parking provision, and in order to encourage the use of sustainable transport in accordance with strategic policy X of the UDP.

The detailed planning application for the school shall include details of a strategy which shall be approved by the local planning authority for the community use of the school facilities outside of normal school hours.  The school shall be operated in accordance with the strategy which shall thereafter be maintained.Reason:In order to promote the provision of adequate community facilities in the local area and in accordance with policy C13 of the UDP.

The residential element of the development permitted shall be begun before the expiration of three years from the date of this permission.Reason:To comply with Section 91 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 (as amended by S.51 of the Planning and Compulsory Purchase Act  2004)

Approval of the details of the access, appearance, landscaping, layout and scale of the proposed school, (hereinafter called "the reserved matters") shall be obtained from the Local Planning Authority, and the development shall not be carried out except in accordance with the details so approved.Reason:The application is in outline only, and these details remain to be submitted and approved.

Application for approval of the reserved matters for the school site shall be made to the Local Planning Authority before the expiration of three years from the date of this outline permission.Reason:To comply with Section 92 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 (as amended by S.51 of the Planning and Compulsory Purchase Act  2004)

No development shall be commenced until a Phasing Plan has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Council as Local Planning Authority.  The development shall be carried out in accordance with the principles of the approved Phasing Plan, unless prior written agreement is obtained from the Council for any variation.Reason:In order to protect the residential amenities of neighbouring occupants and future occupants of the site and to ensure that the details submitted pursuant to conditions can be considered on a phased basis.

No development within any phase (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall commence until there has been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority a scheme of landscaping for that phase of the development which shall include indications of all existing trees, shrubs and hedgerows on the site and details of those to be retained.Reason:To safeguard and improve the appearance of the area and in accordance with policy DE17 of the UDP.

All areas of the residential development identified as public realm on the approved drawings shall be maintained as such and shall be made available for the use of all residents and visitors to the site and notwithstanding the provisions of the Town and Country Planning (General Permitted Development) Order 1995 (or any Order revoking and re-enacting that Order) no fences or other boundaries shall be erected curtailing access to such areas, unless otherwise agreed in writing by the local planning authority.Reason:In order to ensure access to recreational and play spaces and to promote an inclusive community in accordance with policy H18 of the UDP.

The landscaping scheme as approved in accordance with condition 6 shall be carried out for each phase in the first planting and seeding seasons following the occupation of any building within that phase.  Any trees or plants which within a period of 5 years from the completion of the development phase (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5), die, are removed or become seriously damaged or diseased, shall be replaced in the next planting season with others of similar size and species unless the Local Planning Authority gives written consent to any variation.Reason:To secure the provision and retention of the landscaping in the interests of the visual amenity of the area and in accordance with policy DE17 of the UDP.

No phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall commence until a scheme (showing those areas within that phase to be hard landscaped, and the details of that hard landscaping) has been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority in writing.  The details shall include the design of the play areas and street furniture.  The scheme as approved shall be carried out for each phase prior to the occupation of any building within that phase and thereafter permanently retained.Reason:To ensure the development is satisfactorily landscaped in order to improve the visual appearance of the area and in accordance with policy DE16 of the UDP.

A Landscape and Ecological Management Plan shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of the development.  The plan shall specify a management regime designed to promote bio-diversity and provide an attractive well managed public realm.  The plan shall be implemented for each phase prior to the occupation of any residential unit within that phase and shall thereafter be maintained.Reason:In order to ensure a good standard of residential amenity and to promote bio-diversity in accordance with policies H15, DE17, and G46 of the UDP.

No phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall be commenced until a public art strategy for that phase of the development has been submitted to and approved by the local planning authority.  The strategy shall demonstrate artistic involvement in the design of the play spaces and Building K.  The strategy shall be implemented in accordance with the approved details.Reason:In order to provide a good standard of residential amenity and an interesting and stimulating local environment in accordance with policies DE16 and AT8 of the UDP.

No phase of the permitted development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall take place until the applicant has secured the implementation of a programme of recording and historic analysis for that phase, which considers building structure, architectural detail and archaeological evidence.  This shall be undertaken in accordance with a written scheme of investigation which shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of the development.Reason:In order to preserve for posterity records of the use and development of the site and in accordance with policy DE36 of the UDP.

No phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall commence until details/samples of all facing materials to be used in that phase have been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority and no facing materials shall be used except those so approved.Reason:To safeguard the appearance of the development and maintain the appearance of the area and in accordance with policy DE1 of the UDP.

No phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall commence until details of all boundary fences and walls for that phase have been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority and no phase of the development shall be occupied until the approved fences and walls for that phase have been provided.  The approved fences and walls shall be retained unless the Local Planning Authority gives prior written approval to their removal. Reason:To safeguard the appearance of the development and to ensure adequate privacy to future occupants and in accordance with policy DE1 of the UDP.

No phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall be commenced until details of the dustbin enclosures for that phase have been submitted to and approved by the local planning authority. The dustbin enclosures shall be provided in accordance with the approved details. Reason:To provide satisfactory refuse storage provision in the interests of the appearance of the site and locality in accordance with the requirements of Appendix 4 of the UDP.

No phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall commence until a scheme showing the provisions to be made for external lighting, CCTV coverage, access control, and any other measures to reduce the risk of crime for that phase, have been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.  No residential unit within any phase shall be occupied until the approved scheme for that phase has been implemented.  Thereafter the approved measures shall be permanently retained unless otherwise agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority. Reason:In order to provide a good standard of security to future occupants and to reduce the risk of crime in accordance with policy DE6 of the UDP.

No phase shall be commenced (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) until details of the entrance arrangements of the pedestrian and vehicular entrances to the hereby approved blocks of flats or the retained block within that phase have been submitted to and approved by the local planning authority . The details shall be designed to maximise security and to reduce the risk of crime.  The development shall be implemented in accordance with the approved details which shall thereafter be maintained. Reason:In order to provide a good standard of design and security to future occupants and to reduce the risk of crime in accordance with policies DE1 and DE6 of the UDP.

All residential units hereby approved are to comply with Lifetime Homes Standards, as defined in the Joseph Rowntree Foundation publication Achieving Part M and Lifetime Home Standards April 1999 and the joint collaboration of JRF, Mayor of London, GML Architects and Habinteg HA in the publication Lifetime Homes and as referred to in the GLA Accessible London SPG (Appendix 4 correct at March 2004), unless otherwise agreed in writing by the local planning authority.  Reason:In order to ensure that the residential units are adaptable to provide suitable accommodation for disabled or infirm residents in accordance with policy 3A.5 of the London Plan.

Prior to the commencement of the development details shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority specifying the design and location of the wheelchair accessible units or those easily adaptable for residents who are wheelchair users which shall comprise 10% of residential units in the development.  The specified units shall be constructed to wheelchair housing standards in accordance with the publication Wheelchair Housing Design Guide, Second Edition, produced by Stephen Thorpe and Habinteg Housing Association. Reason:In order to meet the housing needs of disabled residents and in accordance with policy 3A.5 of the London Plan.

No satellite dishes may be installed on the exterior of any of the approved blocks of flat or the retained Building A, with the exception of a roof mounted dish providing a communal system available to each resident of the block, and no satellite dish may be installed on the front or side elevation of any house within the development unless otherwise agreed in writing by the local planning authority. Reason:In order to prevent clutter which would detract from the design of the buildings and be harmful to visual amenity and in accordance with policy DE1 of the UDP.

Notwithstanding the provisions of the Town and Country Planning (General Permitted Development) Order 1995 (or any Order revoking and re-enacting that Order) no fences, walls or other boundaries shall be erected, and no hard standing shall be installed within the front garden of any house within the development except for any such details approved pursuant to conditions attached to this permission, unless otherwise agreed in writing by the local planning authority. Reason:In order to maintain the visual appearance of the street scene and to prevent harm to its appearance resulting from such development and in accordance with policy DE1 of the UDP.

No phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under Condition 5) shall commence until a Construction Management Plan incorporating details of the sourcing of materials and waste management has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.  Once approved this plan shall be adhered to throughout the construction period. Reason:In the interests of ensuring sustainable construction practices and in accordance with policies G31 of the Unitary Development Plan and 2A.1 of the London Plan.

No external construction works, deliveries, external running of plant and equipment or internal works audible outside the site boundary shall take place on the site other than between the hours of 0800 to 1800 on Monday to Friday and 0800 to 1300 on Saturday and not at all on Sundays, Public or Bank Holidays without the prior written permission of the Local Planning Authority. Reason:To ensure that the proposed construction work does not cause undue nuisance and disturbance to neighbouring properties at unreasonable hours and in accordance with policy G36 of the UDP.

No  phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall commence until a scheme specifying the provisions to be made to control noise emanating from the site during the construction of that phase has been submitted to, and approved by, the Local Planning Authority.  This scheme should include details of the construction methods to be employed, for example piling, the duration of such activities, the equipment to be used and the proposed hours of operation.  The scheme shall also cover noise resulting from the construction of the phase which emanates from outside the defined area of the phase in question, for example noise from construction traffic.  The scheme shall be implemented in accordance with the approved details and all construction activities associated with the development shall be carried out in accordance with the recommendations contained in British Standard 5228, Parts 1 and 2, 1997 and Part 4, 1997 and any subsequent amendments. Reason:To ensure that the proposed construction work does not cause nuisance and disturbance to neighbouring occupiers and in accordance with Policy G.36 of the UDP.

No phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) shall commence until a scheme specifying the provisions to be made to control dust emanating from that phase has been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority.  The scheme shall also cover dust resulting from the construction of the phase which emanates from outside the defined area of the phase in question, for example dust from construction traffic. The approved scheme shall be implemented and maintained throughout the construction period.Reason:To ensure that the proposed construction work does not cause nuisance, disturbance or health risk to neighbouring occupiers and in accordance with Policy G.39 of the UDP.

Vehicle wheel washing facilities shall be provided on site in accordance with details submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of any demolition/building work on site, and no work shall take place at any time that such wheel washing facilities are not operating. Reason:In order to prevent mud on the adjacent roads in the interest of highway safety and visual amenity.

No phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under condition 5) approved by this permission shall be commenced unless the method for piling foundations for that phase has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority . The piling shall thereafter be undertaken only in accordance with the approved details. Reason:In order to ensure that the work is carried out without causing undue disturbance to neighbouring occupiers or to ground conditions in accordance with policies G36 and G28 of the UDP.

No phase of the development (phasing as shall have been approved under Condition 5), shall be commenced until an Arboricultural Method Statement with Tree Protection Plan devised in accordance with BS5837: 2005 indicating retained trees, trees to be removed, the precise location and design of protective barriers and ground protection, service routing and space for site storage and other construction related facilities has been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority.  The development shall be carried out in accordance with the approved details and any trees that are damaged or felled during construction work (other than those which are shown to be removed on a plan which has been approved under details submitted pursuant to condition 6) must be replaced with semi mature trees of the same or similar species.Reason:To ensure the safety and well-being of the trees on the site that are to remain after building and in accordance with policy DE17.

No phase of the development shall be occupied until the surface level, ground floor and basement car parking areas indicated on the approved drawings for that phase have been constructed and marked out in accordance with the approved drawings.  The parking areas shall thereafter be retained permanently for the accommodation of vehicles of occupiers and visitors to the premises and not used for any other purpose.Reason:To ensure that sufficient off-street parking areas are provided and not to prejudice the free flow of traffic on the adjoining highway and in accordance with Policy T.24 of the Unitary Development Plan.

Any garages shall only be used for the accommodation of motor vehicles incidental to the use of a dwelling house as a residence and shall not be used as living accommodation.Reason:In order to prevent on street parking congestion harmful to residential amenity, visual appearance, and the free flow of traffic and in accordance with policy T24 of the UDP.
borough: London Borough of Barking and Dagenham
